## Directory layout

```
problem/            # READ-ONLY symlink to sol-execbench data -- DO NOT modify
  definition.json   # Formal I/O spec, axis ranges, dtype info
  reference.py      # Baseline implementation (your starting point)
  workload.jsonl    # Test workloads used by the evaluator
candidates/         # Your implementation attempts
solution.py         # Symlink to the promoted candidate (best so far)
docs/               # Analysis and planning documents
outputs/            # Benchmark CSVs and trace JSONs
profile/            # NCU profiling reports
runs/               # Session logs
```

## Constraints

1. **Never modify anything under `problem/`** -- it is a read-only symlink.
2. Your solution must export a `run()` function with the **exact same signature** as `problem/reference.py`.
3. All tensor dtypes and shapes must match the reference outputs exactly.
4. You may use PyTorch, Triton, or custom CUDA extensions.

## Workflow

### 1. Write a candidate

Create `candidates/candidate_NNN.py` (starting from 001). Each candidate must export the same `run()` function.

### 2. Validate correctness

```bash
gpu-run.sh uv run --project /mnt/public/zhaotianlang/projects/kernel-agent/sol-execbench scripts/run_dataset.py problem/ --solution-name candidates/candidate_NNN.py -o outputs/traces --timeout 120
```

This runs the candidate against all workloads and checks output correctness. **All workloads must pass before benchmarking.**

### 3. Benchmark performance

```bash
gpu-run.sh uv run --project /mnt/public/zhaotianlang/projects/kernel-agent/sol-execbench scripts/run_dataset.py problem/ --solution-name candidates/candidate_NNN.py -o outputs/traces --timeout 300 --iterations 50
```

### 4. Promote the best candidate

```bash
cp candidates/candidate_NNN.py solution.py
```

Then validate solution.py:

```bash
gpu-run.sh uv run --project /mnt/public/zhaotianlang/projects/kernel-agent/sol-execbench scripts/run_dataset.py problem/ --solution-name solution.py -o outputs/traces --timeout 120
```

### 5. Iterate

Read benchmark traces in `outputs/traces/` to identify remaining bottlenecks. Use NCU profiling if needed:

```bash
gpu-run.sh ncu --set full -o profile/candidate_NNN <kernel-launch-command>
```

Then write the next candidate incorporating improvements.

## Benchmark evaluation

```bash
gpu-run.sh uv run --project /mnt/public/zhaotianlang/projects/kernel-agent/sol-execbench scripts/run_dataset.py problem/ --solution-name solution.py -o outputs/traces --timeout 300 --iterations 50
```

The SOL score in the output measures your solution's throughput relative to hardware peak. Higher is better.
